{"title_page": "Sara Bareilles", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=November 2018}}\n{{short description|American singer-songwriter, actress, and author.}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Sara Bareilles\n| image              = Sara Bareilles 10 13 2015 (36191615226).jpg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = Bareilles performing at the [[Troubadour (West Hollywood, California)|Troubadour]] in [[West Hollywood, California]] in October 2015\n| birth_name         = Sara Beth Bareilles\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1979|12|07}}\n| birth_place        = [[Eureka, California]], U.S.\n| alma_mater         = [[University of California, Los Angeles]]\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Singer-songwriter|actress}}\n| years_active       = 1998\u2013present\n| partner            = [[Joe Tippett]] (2016\u2013)<ref>https://www.instagram.com/p/B2smMihgibu/</ref>\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist\n  | embed             = yes\n  | background        = solo_singer\n  | instrument        = {{hlist|Vocals|piano|guitar}}\n  | genre             = {{hlist|[[Pop music|Pop]]|[[pop rock]]|[[Soul music|soul]]}}\n  | label             = [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n  | associated_acts   = {{hlist|[[Ingrid Michaelson]]|[[Seth MacFarlane]]}}\n  | website           = {{URL|https://www.sarabmusic.com/}}\n  }}\n}}\n\n'''Sara Beth Bareilles''' ({{IPAc-en|b|\u0259|\u02c8|r|\u025b|l|\u1d7b|s}}, {{respell|b\u0259-RELL-iss}}; born December 7, 1979)<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p739069/biography|pure_url=yes}}|title=Sara Bareilles|last=Lymangrover|first=Jason|year=2007|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=November 28, 2009}}</ref> is an American singer-songwriter and actress. Her 2007 [[hit single]] [[Love Song (Sara Bareilles song)|\"Love Song\"]] reached no. 4 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart.<ref>Love Song \u2013 Sara Bareilles. This came after her strong showing on [[The Voice (franchise)|''The Voice'']] as a first-year contestant. [{{BillboardURLbyName|artist=sara bareilles|chart= all}} Billboard.com]</ref> In the third season of [[NBC]]'s ''[[The Sing-Off]]'', Bareilles served as a celebrity judge alongside [[Ben Folds]] and [[Shawn Stockman]]. She composed music and wrote lyrics for the [[Broadway musical]] ''[[Waitress (musical)|Waitress]]'', for which she earned a [[Tony Award]] nomination for [[Tony Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]] in 2016, and a [[Grammy]] nomination for [[Grammy Award for Best Musical Theater Album|Best Musical Theatre Album]]. In April 2018, Bareilles received acclaim for her portrayal of [[Mary Magdalene]] in [[NBC]]'s [[Jesus Christ Superstar Live in Concert|live television concert adaptation]] of [[Andrew Lloyd Webber]] and [[Tim Rice]]'s rock opera ''[[Jesus Christ Superstar]]'', for which she was nominated for the 2018 [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Limited Series or Movie]].\n\nBareilles has sold over one million albums and over nine million singles and downloads in the [[United States]] and has earned eight [[Grammy Award]] nominations, including one [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]] nomination for ''[[The Blessed Unrest]]'' (2013). She eventually won for the song \"Saint Honesty\" from the album ''[[Amidst the Chaos]]'' (2019), in the [[Grammy Award for Best American Roots Performance|Best American Roots Performance]] category.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/sara-bareilles|title=Sara Bareilles|date=2019-11-26|website=GRAMMY.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-27}}</ref> In February 2012, [[VH1]] placed Bareilles in the 80th spot of the Top 100 Greatest Women in Music.<ref>{{cite web |last= Graham |first= Mark |title= VH1's 100 Greatest Women in Music |url= http://www.vh1.com/music/tuner/2012-02-13/vh1s-100-greatest-women-in-music-complete-list/ |publisher= VH1 |accessdate= February 29, 2012 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://www.webcitation.org/69AQkBrmL?url=http://www.vh1.com/music/tuner/2012-02-13/vh1s-100-greatest-women-in-music-complete-list/ |archivedate= July 15, 2012 |df= mdy }}</ref> Her memoir, ''Sounds Like Me: My Life (So Far) in Song'', was published in 2015; ''[[The New York Times]]'' listed it as a bestseller.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/best-sellers-books/2015-10-25/hardcover-nonfiction/list.html|title=Best Sellers - The New York Times|website=www.nytimes.com|access-date=May 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\n===1979\u20132001: Early life===\nBareilles was born and raised in [[Eureka, California]] in Humboldt County, one of three daughters of Bonnie Halvorsen (n\u00e9e Capellas), a funeral home worker, and Paul Bareilles, an insurance adjuster.<ref>[http://www.newstimes.com/default/article/Sara-Bareilles-does-music-for-love-51667.php Sara Bareilles does music for love] Newstimes.com.</ref><ref>[http://vrouw.nl/site/list_messages/14217]{{dead link|date=September 2011}}</ref> She has two sisters, Stacey and Jennifer, and a half-sister, Melody.<ref>[http://zooeymagazine.com/ Zooey Magazine: Sara Bareilles Cover] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005034025/http://zooeymagazine.com/ |date=October 5, 2013 }} ZooeyMagazine.com</ref> She is of Italian, English,  German, Portuguese, and French descent; she speaks Italian and lived in Italy for a year.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/25-things-you-dont-know-about-me-sara-bareilles-2011710 |title=25 Things You Don't Know About Me: Sara Bareilles |publisher=UsMagazine.com |date=October 7, 2011 |accessdate=July 16, 2012}}</ref> Bareilles was raised [[Roman Catholic|Catholic]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Stevenson|first=Jane|title=The Church of the Redeemer, Toronto \u2013 February 27, 2009|url=http://jam.canoe.ca/Music/Artists/B/Bareilles_Sara/ConcertReviews/2009/02/28/8568531-sun.html|work=Jam!|date=February 27, 2009|accessdate=November 27, 2009}}</ref> She participated in the high school choir, Limited Edition, and local community theater musical productions, including her high school's production of ''[[Little Shop of Horrors (musical)|Little Shop of Horrors]]'', in which she appeared as Audrey.<ref name=\"askmen\">{{cite web|url=http://www.askmen.com/women/singer_300/397c_sara_bareilles.html |title=biography |publisher=Askmen.com |date= |accessdate=September 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\nAfter graduating from high school in 1998, Bareilles studied communication studies at the [[University of California, Los Angeles]],<ref name=\"allmusic\"/> where she was a member of the co-ed [[a cappella]] group Awaken a Cappella;<ref>{{cite web|last=Poder|first=Mindy|title=Little voice, big success|url=http://www.dailybruin.com/articles/2007/7/23/little_voice_big_success/|work=The Daily Bruin|date=July 23, 2007|accessdate=November 27, 2009}}</ref> she can be heard on their album ''Dysfunktional Family'', singing her original selection \"[[Gravity (Sara Bareilles song)|Gravity]]\" and \"[[I Want You Back]]\" by [[The Jackson 5]].<ref name=\"Awaken Dysfunktional Family Album\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rarb.org/reviews/434.html |title=RARB Review of Awaken a cappella: Dysfunktional Family Album |accessdate=July 25, 2006 |first=Elie|last=Landau |author2=Guang Ming Easlon |author3=Joshua Diamant |date=December 26, 2003 |publisher=RARB}}</ref> The group's rendition of Bareilles' \"Gravity\" was featured on the ''Best of College a Cappella 2004'' compilation CD. Bareilles and the band [[Maroon 5]] have been acquainted since their younger days in California, when the band was known as [[Kara's Flowers]].<ref>Bareilles discussed this during an appearance on MTV's ''[[Total Request Live|TRL]]''.{{when|date=April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/sara-bareilles-the-sweet-author-of-tough-songs/|title=Sara Bareilles: The sweet author of tough songs|accessdate=April 2, 2018}}</ref> She performed in the annual student concert [[UCLA Spring Sing]], winning twice. Bareilles taught herself to play the piano and, subsequently, all other instruments she has been seen playing.{{citation needed|date=June 2014}}\n\n===2002\u20132006: Career beginnings and ''Careful Confessions''===\nAfter graduating from [[UCLA]] in 2002, Bareilles performed at local bars and clubs (such as the [[Hotel Caf\u00e9]] and Genghis Cohen in Los Angeles), building a following before performing in larger venues. She released two demos of mostly live tracks in 2003: ''The First One'' in April and ''The Summer Sessions'' in October. In 2004, she appeared as a singer in a bar in the indie film ''[[Girl Play]]'', performing the song \"Undertow\".<ref name=\"askmen\"/>\n\nIn January 2004, Bareilles released her first studio album, ''[[Careful Confessions]]''. She then signed a contract with [[Epic Records]] on April 15, 2005.<ref name=\"Official bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.radioalice.com/pages/1982537.php|title=Sara Bareilles|date=February 2008|work=Radioalice.com|publisher=Epic Records|accessdate=November 27, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081127052042/http://www.radioalice.com/pages/1982537.php|archivedate=November 27, 2008}}</ref> She spent the remainder of the year, and the early months of 2006, writing, composing, and reworking songs for her upcoming album.<ref name=\"allmusic\"/>\n\nIn mid-2004, she opened for [[Rocco DeLuca and the Burden]] during their inaugural headline tour, supported [[Guster]] on their first UK tour, and co-headlined a tour with [[Jon McLaughlin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1679561/|title=Sara Bareilles biography|publisher=IMDb.com|accessdate=July 16, 2013}}</ref> She toured as the opening act in 2006 for Marc Broussard's \"Carencro\" tour. Bareilles's song \"Gravity\" appeared briefly in the 2006 independent film ''[[Loving Annabelle]]''. In 2007, Bareilles toured as the opening act for [[Aqualung (musician)|Aqualung]] and [[Mika (singer)|Mika]], and later that year opened for several shows on both Maroon 5 and [[Paolo Nutini]]'s U.S. tours. She also opened for [[James Blunt]] on his U.S. Tour in association with [[VH1]] You Oughta Know.\n\n===2007\u20132008: Breakthrough with ''Little Voice''===\n[[File:Sara Bareilles.jpg|alt=|thumb|left|Bareilles's success with ''Little Voice'' led her to tour Europe; she is pictured here in her first tour of the Netherlands.]]\nIn June 2007, [[iTunes]] featured Bareilles's single \"[[Love Song (Sara Bareilles song)|Love Song]]\" as the free single of the week. The following month, her major-label debut, ''[[Little Voice (album)|Little Voice]]'', shot to No. 1 on the list of most downloaded albums of the music store<ref>{{cite magazine |title=T.I. Is Top Dog Again on Billboard 200 |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1050989/ti-is-top-dog-again-on-the-billboard-200|magazine=Billboard.com|accessdate=July 16, 2013}}</ref> in its first week of release, and debuted at No. 45 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart. After being featured on a [[Rhapsody (online music service)|Rhapsody]] commercial in 2007, \"Love Song\" began climbing the pop charts, jumping from No. 73 to No. 16 in one week. It entered the top 10 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] on December 27, 2007, and peaked at No. 4. On other charts, such as the Pop 100 and [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Hot AC]], \"Love Song\" hit No. 1. Bareilles performed the song on ''[[The Tonight Show with Jay Leno]]'' on Thursday, January 17, 2008, and on [[Today (NBC program)|the ''Today'' show]] on Thursday, February 21, 2008. Soon after that, the song entered the [[UK Singles Chart]], peaking at No. 4. The music video was directed by [[Josh Forbes]], and it starred the British actor [[Adam Campbell (actor)|Adam Campbell]].\n\nAs of 2010, ''Little Voice'' had been certified platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]]. The album peaked in the ''Billboard'' 200 at No. 7, and the UK Top 40 at No. 9.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1046425/johnsons-static-prevails-again-on-album-chart|title=Johnson's 'Static' Prevails Again on Album Chart|work=Billboard|date=February 27, 2008|accessdate=November 27, 2008}}</ref> Bareilles's breakthrough single, \"Love Song\", was later certified triple platinum.<ref name=\"yahoo sales\">{{cite news |url=https://www.yahoo.com/music/bp/chart-watch--pharrell-steps-up-004435636.html?nf=1 |title=Chart Watch: Pharrell Steps Up | author=Paul Grein |date=April 30, 2014 |accessdate= August 15, 2015 |work=Yahoo Music }}</ref>\n\nOn October 28, 2008, Bareilles released ''Between the Lines: Sara Bareilles Live at the Fillmore'' on DVD and CD. The package is a recording of her first headlining tour at [[The Fillmore]] in San Francisco. This package also included live recordings of her unreleased song \"August Moon\", as well as a cover of [[Otis Redding]]'s \"[[(Sittin' On) The Dock of the Bay]]\". She concluded the tour in her home town of Eureka, California, on December 19, 2008, at the Arkley Center for the Performing Arts.\n\nShe toured with [[Counting Crows]] and Maroon 5 between July 22 and August 26, 2008. The first stop was [[Virginia Beach, Virginia]], and the last stop [[Cuyahoga Falls, Ohio]].<ref>[http://www.maroon5sin.com/live.php] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080328025943/http://www.maroon5sin.com/live.php|date=March 28, 2008}}</ref> Bareilles was selected as MTV artist of the week for July 7\u201311 and appeared again on ''The Tonight Show with Jay Leno'' on Wednesday, July 9, 2008; and on December 9, 2008 (with [[Ingrid Michaelson]]).\n\nDuring the spring of 2009, Bareilles was on her second headlining tour, the Gravity Tour, to promote \"[[Gravity (Sara Bareilles song)|Gravity]]\", the third and final single from her album ''Little Voice''. She made her third appearance in [[Charlottesville, Virginia]], during the [[University of Virginia]]'s annual Springfest on March 28, her first as the opener for Marc Broussard in 2005 and the second being an [[Opening act|opening]] for Maroon 5. Bareilles also played multiple college shows in April and May. Some were for college students only and others were open to the public.\n\nShe sent out a special holiday message to fans on her mailing list and gave out a free live acoustic EP recorded during her Gravity Tour last spring. The EP contained 7 acoustic songs, including a new song \"Free Ride\", \"I'm on Fire\" (a [[Bruce Springsteen]] cover duet with [[Tony Lucca]]), and two speaking segments.\n\nIn early 2010, Bareilles recorded video of what she called \"An Ode to ''[[Jersey Shore (TV series)|Jersey Shore]]''\" and posted it to her official website as a gag for fans.<ref>[http://www.sarabmusic.com/site.html] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100206171755/http://www.sarabmusic.com/site.html|date=February 6, 2010}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n===2009\u20132012: ''Kaleidoscope Heart'' and ''The Sing-Off''===\n[[File:Sara Bareilles Melkweg.JPG|alt=|thumb|180px|Bareilles at De Melkweg, Amsterdam, the Netherlands, June 16, 2008]]\n\nAfter an extended period of [[writer's block]],<ref>{{cite magazine|url= http://www.contactmusic.com/news/sara-bareilles-battle-with-writers-block_1204806|title= Sara Bareilles \u2013 Sara Bareilles' Battle With Writer's Block |magazine=Contactmusic.com |accessdate=October 22, 2011}}</ref> Bareilles began work on the follow-up to her major label debut in the summer of 2009, collaborating with the likes of [[Questlove|Ahmir \"Questlove\" Thompson]], members of [[Weezer]], and [[Pharrell Williams]]. As the songs began to take their final shape, [[Neal Avron]] was assigned to produce, record, and mix the entire album. The album, eventually titled ''[[Kaleidoscope Heart]]'', was recorded at [[The Village Recorder]] and [[Sunset Sound]] in Los Angeles.\n\nThe first single from ''Kaleidoscope Heart'', \"[[King of Anything]]\", began receiving radio airplay in the United States in May 2010,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/sara-bareilles-set-to-release-first-single-king-of-anything-off-forthcoming-new-album-92683379.html |title=Sara Bareilles Set to Release First Single 'King of Anything' Off Forthcoming New Album |location=New York |publisher=Prnewswire.com |date= |accessdate=September 30, 2011}}</ref> and was released for sale in June.<ref name=\"twittersale\">{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/SaraBareilles/status/13745535401|title=Twitter / Sara Bareilles: Quick clarification y'all...|last=Bareilles|first=Sara|year=2010|publisher=Twitter status update|accessdate=May 11, 2010}}</ref>  \"King of Anything\" had its first play on British radio airwaves on Paul Kay's \"Album Download\" show on Mid-Wales commercial radio station [[Radio Maldwyn|\"Radio Maldwyn \u2013 The Magic 756\"]] in August 2010. \"King of Anything\" was later certified platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]].\n\nIn anticipation of the new album, Bareilles released a series of webisodes, featuring the making of select songs from ''Kaleidoscope Heart'', including \"King of Anything\", \"Uncharted\", \"Gonna Get Over You\", \"Bluebird\", and a strings-only version of \"King of Anything\". The first webisode also contains Bareilles writing the chorus/refrain lyrics for \"Hold My Heart\". She was selected as VH1's Posted Artist of the Month for July 2010,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/music/posted/sara-bareilles/index.jhtml#fbid=1Xmulc2pTYp |title=Sara Bareilles Posted |publisher=VH1.com |date=July 1, 2010 |accessdate=September 30, 2011}}</ref> chronicling her life leading up to the album's release.\n\n''Kaleidoscope Heart'' was released on September 7, 2010, and debuted at number 1 in the United States, selling 90,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/956309/sara-bareilles-heart-beats-at-no-1-on-billboard-200|title=Sara Bareilles' 'Heart' Beats at No. 1 on Billboard 200|publisher=}}</ref> Her previous album ''Little Voice'' re-entered the charts at number 200 in the same week, bookending the charts.<ref>Trust, Gary. [http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/956248/ask-billboard-bareilles-bookends-billboard-200 \"Ask Billboard: Sara Bareilles Bookends Billboard 200\"], ''Billboard'', September 17, 2010.</ref>\n\nBareilles toured in support of ''Kaleidoscope Heart'' from September to December 2010, with most of the shows being sold out. Bareilles toured Europe and parts of Asia and Australia with Maroon 5 throughout spring 2011. She embarked on a small headline \"Uncharted\" tour in April 2011 with openers [[Elizabeth & the Catapult]] and [[Ximena Sari\u00f1ana]] in support of the second single from ''Kaleidoscope Heart'', \"[[Uncharted (song)|Uncharted]]\", which concluded April 23, 2011 in Memphis, Tennessee. She also opened select shows for the country music duo [[Sugarland]] on their Summer 2011 Incredible Machine Tour. The third and final single released from ''Kaleidoscope Heart'' is \"Gonna Get Over You\", with a music video directed by [[Jonah Hill]].\n\nBareilles was added in the third season of the NBC television series ''[[The Sing-Off]]'' as a celebrity judge following the departure of [[Nicole Scherzinger]], alongside Ben Folds and Shawn Stockman of [[Boyz II Men]]. Bareilles also guest-starred on ''[[Bucket & Skinner's Epic Adventures]]''.\n\nOn August 13, 2011, the Hoosier Lottery Grandstand stage at the [[Indiana State Fair]] collapsed right after Bareilles finished performing as the opening act for [[Sugarland]]. She was uninjured, tweeting, \"I'm speechless and feel so helpless; my heart aches for the lives lost.\" Seven people were killed, and more than 45 injured, in the collapse.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/US/08/13/indiana.stage.collapse/index.html?iref=NS1 |title=Stage Collapse at Indiana State Fair |publisher=CNN |date=August 13, 2011 |accessdate=September 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===2012\u20132014: ''Once Upon Another Time'' EP and ''The Blessed Unrest''===\nSoon after joining ''The Sing-Off'', Bareilles announced she was in the process of recording a new EP with co-star Ben Folds producing it. She also collaborated with fellow singer songwriters [[Greg Laswell]] and [[Jon McLaughlin]] on their new singles in February. In March, she was slated to release ''A Trace of Sun'', a documentary of the time she had spent volunteering in Japan after the [[2011 Tohoku earthquake]]. Her EP, ''[[Once Upon Another Time]]'', was released on 22 May and contained 5 new recordings. The first and only single from the EP, \"Stay\", was released on April 21, 2012 on 7\" vinyl, exclusive to [[Record Store Day]] participants with a vinyl-only B-side, \"Beautiful Girl\".\nDuring her [[Stageit]] show on September 10, 2012, Bareilles stated that she was working on a new record in New York. She also premiered a new song which might be appearing on the new album in question, which was titled \"Only Shadows\". In January 2013, she revealed the plans for what was to come later in the year. After moving to New York, Bareilles finished her record, and released the lead single from that album \"soon\" thereafter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/SaraBareilles/status/296032882273693697 |title=Twitter / SaraBareilles: Lots of questions on what's |publisher=Twitter.com |date= |accessdate=July 16, 2013}}</ref> In January, Bareilles was a featured artist of the a cappella group [[Straight No Chaser (group)|Straight No Chaser]] on the [[Jackson 5]] song, \"I Want You Back\" which premiered on ''Billboard''.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/1538753/straight-no-chaser-feat-sara-bareilles-i-want-you-back-exclusive|title=Straight No Chaser feat. Sara Bareilles, 'I Want You Back'|magazine=Billboard.com|accessdate=July 16, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2013, Bareilles began teasing her fans to her upcoming album through her Twitter and YouTube accounts. The first tease was a video she released on her website, titled \"Sara is Making a Record...\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jWd-Vvaj1D8 |title=Sara is Making a Record... |publisher=YouTube |date=February 26, 2013 |accessdate=July 16, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, 2013, Bareilles announced that she would conduct an 18-city tour to promote the new album. The first single, \"[[Brave (Sara Bareilles song)|Brave]]\", was released digitally on April 23.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Brave/dp/B00CDU8I6S/ |title=Brave: Sara Bareilles: MP3 Downloads |date= |accessdate=July 16, 2013}}</ref> On April 17, 2013, Bareilles released a lyric video for her single \"Brave\" on YouTube.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xwTr_CRw3GY |title=Sara Bareilles \u2013 Brave (Lyric Video) |publisher=YouTube |date=April 17, 2013 |accessdate=July 16, 2013}}</ref> The album she had been teasing, finally titled ''[[The Blessed Unrest]]'', was eventually released on July 13, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nYTNOOcJq10&list=PLa-JqYjyIqqqQ03Xr6nFgvOcsGtGhT3TW&index=2 |title=Sara Bareilles \u2013 The Blessed Unrest \u2013 Webisode |publisher=YouTube |date=April 17, 2013 |accessdate=July 16, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://artists.letssingit.com/artist-7k7mx/news/491255 |title=Sara Bareilles News \u2013 New Song: Sara Bareilles \u2013 'Brave' |publisher=Artists.letssingit.com |date=April 19, 2013 |accessdate=July 16, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130605044523/http://artists.letssingit.com/artist-7k7mx/news/491255 |archivedate=June 5, 2013  }}</ref>\n\nBareilles performed two songs for the feature film ''[[Bounty Killer (film)|Bounty Killer]]'', which was released in September 2013. The first, titled \"The Kill\", was written and composed by Will Collyer and [[Sujata Day]]. The second, titled \"Gonna Getcha\", was written and composed by Will Collyer and the film's director, Henry Saine.\n\nHer live album, \"[[Brave Enough: Live at the Variety Playhouse]]\", was released on October 22, 2013. The concert was recorded at the [[Variety Playhouse]] in [[Atlanta|Atlanta, Georgia]].<ref name=\"sbbraveenough\">{{cite web |url= http://www.sarabmusic.com/news/solo-and-yolo/|title=Solo and Yolo|accessdate=October 13, 2013|publisher= SaraBareilles.com|year= 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2013, two nurses from [[University of Minnesota Amplatz Children's Hospital]] Brittany Bloemke and Natalie Snyder, along with former patient Sarah Ewald, produced a [[YouTube]] video containing coworkers and young cancer patients dancing and singing to Bareilles's song \"Brave\". As of August, 2019, it had over 1.6 million views.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=N8xnLkyKgsE|title=Brave at U of M Amplatz Children's Hospital|accessdate=August 26, 2019|publisher=YouTube.com}}</ref> On October 31, 2013, while the trio were being interviewed by host [[Nischelle Turner]] on the [[HLN (TV channel)|HLN]] show ''[[Showbiz Tonight]]'', Bareilles surprised them by [[Skype|Skyping]] into the interview. Of the video, she said: \"I was sent this video by a friend of a friend who lives in Minnesota, and I watched it late at night and immediately my eyes welled up with tears. It's moments like this that remind me of the importance of music, and I can't think of a more perfect incarnation of this song. It's exactly the kind of thing that gives the life to this song that we were hoping for.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/11/01/sara-bareilles-surprises-nurses_n_4194531.html|title=Sara Bareilles Surprises Nurses Behind Amplatz Children's Hospital's 'Brave' Cover | work=Huffington Post | first=Mohini|last=Kundu|date=November 1, 2013}}</ref> On October 16, 2019 she visited the hospital before her show at the Xcel Energy center to sing the song with them live.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fox9.com/news/sara-bareilles-sings-brave-with-u-of-m-masonic-childrens-hospital-staff-and-patients|title=Sara Bareilles sings 'Brave' with U of M Masonic Children's Hospital staff and patients|date=2019-10-16|website=FOX 9|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\nOn January 26, 2014, Bareilles performed a duet with [[Carole King]] at the [[56th Annual Grammy Awards]]. The pair performed renditions of King's \"Beautiful\" and Bareilles's \"Brave\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Lewis|first=Randy|title=Carole King-Sara Bareilles duet soars at Grammy Awards - lattices.com|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/music/la-et-ms-grammys-carole-king-sara-bareilles-duet-20140127,0,1068189.story#axzz2reLqyIVM|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=January 27, 2014|date=January 27, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn April 28, 2014, Bareilles performed with [[Elton John]] at [[The Breast Cancer Research Foundation]]'s Annual Hot Pink Party Fundraiser.<ref>{{cite web|title=Elton to Play Hot Pink Party in NYC on April 28|url=http://www.eltonjohn.com/elton-to-play-hot-pink-party-in-nyc-on-april-28/|publisher=EltonJohn.com|accessdate=April 30, 2014|date=April 18, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sara Bareilles And Elton John|url=http://www.grammy.com/photos/sara-bareilles-and-elton-john|publisher=GRAMMY.com|accessdate=April 30, 2014|date=April 29, 2014}}</ref> In May, Bareilles recorded a cover of [[Jackie Wilson]]'s song \"[[(Your Love Keeps Lifting Me) Higher and Higher]]\" for the [[Oprah Winfrey Network (U.S. TV channel)|Oprah Winfrey Network]].<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Watch Sara Bareilles Cover 'Higher and Higher' for Oprah's TV Network|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/videos/watch-sara-bareilles-cover-higher-and-higher-for-oprahs-tv-network-20140509|magazine=Rolling Stone|accessdate=May 10, 2014|date=May 9, 2014}}</ref>\n\nBareilles toured 24 American cities between July 10, 2014 and August 14, 2014 in her \"The Little Black Dress Summer Tour\". The tour supported her album ''[[The Blessed Unrest]]'', and it featured opening performances by at least three \"special guests\": American singer [[Emily King]], indie pop band [[Lucius (band)|Lucius]], and Canadian singer [[Hannah Georgas]].\n\nBareilles sang \"[[Smile (Charlie Chaplin song)|Smile]]\" during the \"In Memoriam\" segment of the [[66th Primetime Emmy Awards]] show on August 25, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sara Bareilles + Billy Crystal Lead Moving 'In Memoriam' Tribute at Emmys|url=http://popcrush.com/sara-bareilles-billy-crystal-robin-williams-in-memoriam-emmys/|publisher=popcrush.com|date=August 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2015\u20132017: ''Waitress'', ''Sounds Like Me'', and ''What's Inside''===\nIn June 2013, it was reported that Bareilles was to score ''[[Waitress (musical)|Waitress]]'', a musical adaptation of [[Waitress (film)|the 2007 film of the same title]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadway.com/buzz/170011/sara-bareilles-to-score-new-musical-adaptation-of-waitress-directed-by-diane-paulus/|title=Sara Bareilles to Score New Musical Adaptation of Waitress, Directed by Diane Paulus|publisher=Broadway.com|date=June 9, 2013}}</ref> The musical opened on August 20, 2015, produced by the [[American Repertory Theater]].<ref name=billboard-waitress>{{cite web|title=Sara Bareilles' 'Waitress' Musical To Debut In August|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6523952/sara-bareilles-waitress-musical|website=Billboard|publisher=Billboard|accessdate=April 21, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/08/13/waitress-musical-sets-the-table-for-broadway/?_r=0|title='Waitress' Musical Sets the Table for Broadway|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=October 28, 2015}}</ref> The production was directed by [[Diane Paulus]], and it starred [[Jessie Mueller]] in the leading role.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jessie Mueller to star in Sara Bareilles's 'Waitress'|url=http://gulfnews.com/life-style/celebrity/jessie-mueller-to-star-in-sara-bareilles-s-waitress-1.1493583|website=Gulf News|publisher=Al Nisr Publishing LLC|accessdate=April 21, 2015}}</ref> Bareilles debuted a song from the musical, \"[[She Used to Be Mine (Sara Bareilles song)|She Used To Be Mine]],\" during some shows on her Little Black Dress Tour.<ref name=sutbm-youtube>{{cite web|title=Sara Bareilles \u2013 \"She Used To Be Mine\" from Waitress \u2013 Berkeley, CA 8/14/14|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8tpg792CiIg|website=YouTube|publisher=Just Jared|accessdate=April 21, 2015}}</ref> On July 16, 2019 it was announced that ''Waitress'' would end its run on Broadway on January 5, 2020.<ref name=\"McPhee\">{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/waitress-to-end-broadway-run|title=Waitress to End Broadway Run|last=McPhee|first=Ryan|date=July 16, 2019|website=Playbill|accessdate=2019-07-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sara-bareilles-broadway-hit-waitress-end-four-year-run-1224383|title=Sara Bareilles' Broadway Hit 'Waitress' to End Four-Year Run (Exclusive)|website=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=2019-07-19}}</ref> Bareilles said about the closing, \u201cIt is such a bittersweet moment to say goodbye to our home on Broadway at the Brooks Atkinson Theatre, but I am reflecting upon this enormously magical time with a tremendous amount of gratitude...and smiling through tears. I am in awe of the tireless energy and devotion of our company, our crew, our band, and most especially our fans. The warmth and love they have showered upon our show in all its iterations is truly a miracle, and the impact this experience has had on my life has been profound and unforgettable. Thank you to my dear collaborators and producers, the entirety of our wildly passionate ''Waitress'' company, band and crew members (past and present), our beloved staff at the Brooks, and a very special thank you to our ''Waitress'' fans and believers who have made this chapter as sweet as it ever could have been. The run of ''Waitress'' on Broadway has far surpassed my expectations and I am so very proud of what we were able to create here in New York City, but I am still so moved and delighted by the knowledge that our show will continue to have a big, beautiful life in other cities around the world, and on tour. Alas... everything changes. Sugar, Butter, Thank you.<ref name=\"McPhee\"/>\"\n\nOn October 25, 2012, [[Simon & Schuster]] announced it would publish a book, written by Bareilles, containing essays and photos.<ref name=\"simonandschuster\">{{cite web|url=http://d2ikrwcyurm5yv.buttfront.net/press_releases/%20-%20Press%20Releases/Sara%20Bareilles.pdf|title=Simon & Schuster to Publish a Book by Platinum Selling Singer-Songwriter Sara Bareilles|publisher=Simon & Schuster|date=October 25, 2012}}</ref> The book was tentatively set for release in 2014; however, Bareilles finished the book in March 2015.<ref name=instagram-book>{{cite web|title=MY BOOK MY BOOK MY BOOK MY BOOK!!!!!|last1=Bareilles|first1=Sara|url=https://instagram.com/p/0dza56jGIF/|website=Instagram|accessdate=April 21, 2015}}</ref> The title, ''Sounds Like Me: My Life (So Far) in Song'', was announced in April 2015,<ref>{{cite web|title=Sounds Like Me {{ndash}} Book by Sara Bareilles|url=http://books.simonandschuster.com/Sounds-Like-Me/Sara-Bareilles/9781476727776|website=Simon & Schuster|publisher=CBS Corporation|accessdate=May 1, 2015}}</ref> and the book released on October 6, 2015.<ref name=\"Bareilles2015\">{{cite book |last=Bareilles |first=Sara |title=Sounds Like Me: My Life (So Far) in Song |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ptqxCAAAQBAJ |date=October 6, 2015 |publisher=Simon & Schuster |isbn=978-1-4767-2778-3}}</ref>\n\nBareilles began work on her fifth studio album, ''[[What's Inside: Songs from Waitress]]'',<ref name=\"playbill\">{{cite web|title=Make it \"Mine\": Listen to Sara Bareilles Single from \"What's Inside: Songs from Waitress\"|last1=Gans|first1=Andrew|last2=Viagas|first2=Robert|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/make-it-mine-listen-to-sara-bareilles-single-from-whats-inside-songs-from-waitress-364212|website=Playbill.com|publisher=Playbill|date=September 25, 2015|accessdate=October 4, 2015}}</ref> in April 2015 at [[New York City]]'s [[Electric Lady Studios]], in collaboration with producer [[Neal Avron]], who had previously worked with Bareilles on ''Kaleidoscope Heart''.<ref>{{cite web|title=This is happening.|last1=Bareilles|first1=Sara|url=https://instagram.com/p/1botm5jGMm/|website=Instagram|accessdate=April 21, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=My home last week at Electric Lady Studios...|last1=Scharff|first1=Jared|url=https://instagram.com/p/1t1DcKwNwE/|website=Instagram|accessdate=April 21, 2015}}</ref> In June 2015, Bareilles confirmed, during a Google Hangout Q & A session, that the album would feature songs she had written and composed for ''Waitress'', which would be reworked \"to sound like Sara Bareilles songs.\" On June 27, 2015, Bareilles and Nadia DiGiallonardo performed \"She Used To Be Mine,\" the album's [[lead single]], with [[Rich Dworsky]] and The Berkshire Boys on humorist [[Garrison Keillor]]'s National Public Radio show ''[[A Prairie Home Companion]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=She Used To Be Mine \u2013 Sara Bareilles and Nadia DiGiallonardo \u2013 6/27/2015|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Pw4VVC5K9Yw|website=YouTube|accessdate=June 29, 2015}}</ref> The album was released on November 6, 2015, through [[Epic Records]].\n\nIn June 2016, Bareilles performed the part of Ariel in a two-night live presentation of [[The Little Mermaid (1989 film)|Disney's ''The Little Mermaid'']] at the [[Hollywood Bowl]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatermania.com/los-angeles-theater/news/hollywood-bowl-little-mermaid-begins-performances_77296.html|title=Hollywood Bowl's The Little Mermaid, Starring Sara Bareilles, Set to Begin|accessdate=June 11, 2018}}</ref> She performed the [[Joni Mitchell]] song \"[[Both Sides, Now]]\" during the ''In Memoriam'' homage at the [[89th Academy Awards]] in February 2017.\n\nOn March 31, 2017, Bareilles took to the Broadway stage in the role of Jenna Hunterson in ''Waitress'' for a 10-week engagement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.today.com/video/sara-bareilles-reveals-she-is-taking-over-lead-role-of-watiress-on-broadway-878693443516|title=Sara Bareilles reveals she is taking over lead role of 'Watiress' on Broadway|website=TODAY.com|access-date=March 2, 2017}}</ref> She would return to the role in January 2018 for a 6-week run, including 2 weeks co-starring with friend and fellow musician [[Jason Mraz]] as Dr. Pomatter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.broadway.com/buzz/189836/sara-bareilles-to-return-to-her-broadway-musical-waitress-jason-mraz-extends-run/|title=Sara Bareilles Will Return to Her Broadway Musical Waitress; Jason Mraz Extends Run|website=Broadway}}</ref> Mraz had previously duetted with Bareilles on two songs featuring the Pomatter part on the ''What's Inside'' album. She returned to the role again in January 2019, for a 4-week run opposite [[Gavin Creel]] as Dr. Pomatter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/sara-bareilles-returns-to-broadways-waitress-opposite-tony-winner-gavin-creel-january-7|title=Sara Bareilles Returns to Broadway's Waitress Opposite Tony Winner Gavin Creel January 7|website=Playbill}}</ref>\n\n===2018\u2013present: ''Jesus Christ Superstar'' and ''Amidst the Chaos''===\nOn April 1, 2018, Bareilles portrayed [[Mary Magdalene]] in ''[[Jesus Christ Superstar Live in Concert]]'', [[NBC]]'s stripped-down \"concert\" adaptation of [[Andrew Lloyd Webber]] and [[Tim Rice]]'s first full stage musical.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lefkowitz |first1=Andy |title=Sara Bareilles to Play Mary Magdalene in NBC's Jesus Christ Superstar Live in Concert |url=https://www.broadway.com/buzz/190833/sara-bareilles-to-play-mary-magdalene-in-nbcs-jesus-christ-superstar-live-in-concert/ |website=Broadway |date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> Bareilles was well-received in the role by fans and critics and was nominated for the 2018 [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Limited Series or Movie]].<ref name=\"SB Emmys 2018\">{{cite web |last=Mallikarjuna |first=Krutika |url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/sara-bareilles-gets-emmy-nom-for-jesus-christ-superstar/ |title=Sara Bareilles Gets Surprise Emmy Nomination for Jesus Christ Superstar |work=TV Guide |date=July 13, 2018 |accessdate=October 25, 2018}}</ref> and the 2019 [[Grammy Award for Best Musical Theater Album|Grammy Award for Best Musical Theatre Album]].\n\nOn June 10, 2018, Bareilles hosted the [[72nd Tony Awards]] with [[Josh Groban]]. She and Groban performed the opening number to the show, \"This One's For You\", which was an ode to those who would not win an award that night and referencing that neither had won a major award before, particularly noting the [[Grammy Awards]]. They also performed three other numbers, a medley tribute to [[Chita Rivera]] and [[Andrew Lloyd Webber]], \"8 Times a Week\" (a parody of \"[[Chandelier (song)|Chandelier]]\" by [[Sia (musician)|Sia]]), and \"This One's for the Dreamers\". Bareilles was one of the composers who were nominated for the 2018 [[Tony Award for Best Original Score]] for ''[[SpongeBob SquarePants (musical)|SpongeBob SquarePants]]''. In August 2018, it was announced that ''Waitress'' would premiere at the [[Adelphi Theatre]] in [[London]]'s [[West End theatre|West End]] in February 2019.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gans|first=Andrew|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/waitress-will-open-in-londons-west-end-in-2019|title=Waitress Will Open in London's West End in 2019|date=August 21, 2018|accessdate=October 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2017, Bareilles announced that she was working on a new album to be released by the end of 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ew.com/music/2017/01/11/sara-bareilles-new-pop-album-2017/ |title=Sara Bareilles reveals how Broadway helped her prepare for new pop album |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=January 11, 2017 |accessdate=May 8, 2017 |author=Goodman, Jessica}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Sara-Bareilles-Working-on-New-Record-Eyeing-Starring-Role-in-WAITRESS-20170110 |title=Sara Bareilles Working on New Record, Eyeing Starring Role in Waitress? |work=Broadway World |date=January 10, 2017 |accessdate=May 8, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://hellogiggles.com/sara-bareilles-new-album-2017/ |title=Sara Bareilles talks new album and we have one question \u2014 will she write us a love song? |work=Hello Giggles |date=January 11, 2017 |accessdate=May 8, 2017 |author=Horne, Aly}}</ref> The new album's first single, \"Armor,\" was released on October 26, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bareilles|first=Sara|url=https://twitter.com/SaraBareilles?ref_src=twsrc%5Egoogle%7Ctwcamp%5Eserp%7Ctwgr%5Eauthor|title=Sara Bareilles Announces 'Armor' Single|date=October 24, 2018|accessdate=October 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Bowenbank|first=Starr|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8481580/sara-bareilles-new-music-armor-cover-art|title=Sara Bareilles Announces New Song 'Armor'|date=October 24, 2018|accessdate=October 25, 2018}}</ref> The same day, pre-orders for the new album were made available through the [[PledgeMusic]] [[direct-to-fan]] platform with an updated release target of Spring 2019.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bareilles|first=Sara|url=https://twitter.com/SaraBareilles/status/1055946803755905024|title=Sara Bareilles Announces PledgeMusic Pre-Order|date=October 26, 2018|accessdate=October 26, 2018}}</ref> On February 13, 2019, Bareilles announced the title of her sixth album will be ''[[Amidst the Chaos]]''. On April 6, 2019, the album debuted at number six on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] with 35,000 [[equivalent album sales]], of which 29,000 were pure sales.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8507048/khalid-free-spirit-debuts-at-no-1-on-billboard-200-albums-chart|title=Khalid's 'Free Spirit' Debuts at No. 1 on Billboard 200 Albums Chart|last=Caulfield|first=Keith  |date=April 14, 2019|website=Billboard|access-date=April 14, 2019}}</ref> She also released \"Shiny,\" a song about \"wanting moms to see how special they really are,\" on May 10, 2019 to coincide with Mother's Day.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Blistein |first1=Jon |title=Hear Sara Bareilles' Poignant New Mother's Day Song 'Shiny' |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/sara-bareilles-new-song-shiny-mothers-day-834033/ |website=Rolling Stone |date=May 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn January 27, 2020, Bareilles made her [[West End theatre|West End]] debut, as Jenna Hunterson in ''Waitress'' at the [[Adelphi Theatre]], opposite [[Gavin Creel]] as Dr. Jim Pomatter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B4cVq62ANiS/|title=Sara Bareilles on Instagram: \"Sweetest announcement alert!! I'm thrilled to finally share the news that I'm headed over the pond to play Jenna with my #WaitressLondon\u2026\"|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=November 5, 2019}}</ref> Bareilles was set to have a limited eight weeks run that ends on March 21, but performed her last show on 14 March and returned to the United States due to international travel restrictions regarding the [[coronavirus outbreak]]. <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/theatre/waitress-sara-bareilles-gavin-creel-coronavirus-a4387121.html?amp|title= Waitress stars Sara Bareilles and Gavin Creel to leave West End early over coronavirus travel concerns |publisher=London Evening Standard|last=Embley|first=Jochan|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref> Bareilles also won the [[Grammy Award]] for \"Best American Roots Performance\" for ''Saint Honesty'' from her album ''[[Amidst the Chaos]]'' on January 27, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Haylock |first1=Zoe |title=Billie Eilish Leads The 2020 Grammy Award Winners |url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/01/grammy-winners-2020-the-full-list.html |website=Vulture |language=en-us |date=January 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Artistry==\n\n===Musical style and influences===\nBareilles is known for her strong [[mezzo-soprano]] vocal range.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvovermind.com/entertainment-news/five-things-didnt-know-sara-bareilles|last=Hanson-Firestone|first=Dana|title=Five Things You Didn't Know About Sara Bareilles|date=December 12, 2017|accessdate=March 13, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://rocknycliveandrecorded.com/starbucks-song-of-the-week-i-choose-you-by-sara-bareilles.html|work=Rock NYC|last=Camus|first=Alyson|date=September 2, 2013|accessdate=July 11, 2018|title=Starbucks' Song Of The Week: 'I Choose You' by Sara Bareilles|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180712222011/http://rocknycliveandrecorded.com/starbucks-song-of-the-week-i-choose-you-by-sara-bareilles.html|archive-date=July 12, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> She is often compared to artists such as [[Regina Spektor]], [[Fiona Apple]] and [[Billy Joel]],<ref name=cduniv>[http://www.cduniverse.com/productinfo.asp?pid=7624153 \"Sara Bareilles Little Voice (2-CD Set) CD\" review on CD Universe]. Retrieved on December 11, 2008.</ref> due to her vocal ability and incorporation of piano into her music.\n\nShe has described her sound as \"piano-based pop soul\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jJAkXleNUwo |title=UK's ''Daily Mirror'' interview of Bareilles on YouTube |publisher=Youtube.com |date=June 16, 2008 |accessdate=September 30, 2011}}</ref> with Bareilles finding inspiration from singers such as [[Etta James]] and [[Sam Cooke]].<ref name=\"movietome.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.movietome.com/people/608267/sara-bareilles/trivia.html |title=Need new link |publisher=Movietome.com |date= |accessdate=September 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\nShe is often praised for her songwriting abilities, with critics stating she \"conveys vulnerability and wisdom in lyrics that speak honestly about relationships from a woman's point of view\", and that her \"writing voice is uniquely her own\".<ref name=cduniv/>\n\n===Band members===\n[[File:Sara and the band.jpg|alt=Sara and the band|thumb|right|Bareilles and her former band during her ''[[Kaleidoscope Heart Tour]]'' at the Warfield on December 16, 2010. Left to right: Javier Dunn, Bareilles, Philip Krohnengold, Josh Day, and Daniel Rhine.]]\nBareilles's first band consisted of these members aside from Bareilles herself:\n* Javier Dunn (guitar and vocals),<ref>Khoury, Rania. [http://www.pegasusnews.com/news/2010/oct/03/concert-review-sara-bareilles-greg-laswell/ \"Concert review and photos: Sara Bareilles, Greg Laswell, Javier Dunn at Palladium Ballroom (October 2)\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101017040721/http://www.pegasusnews.com/news/2010/oct/03/concert-review-sara-bareilles-greg-laswell/ |date=October 17, 2010 }}, Pegasusnews.com, October 3, 2010.</ref>\n* Daniel Rhine (bass), and\n* Josh Day (drums, percussion and backing vocals).<ref>Jayvee. [http://theround-table.blogspot.com/2009/02/tony-lucca-sara-bareilles-play-joes-pub.html \"Tony Lucca & Sara Bareilles Play Joe's Pub in NYC\"], The Round Table blog, February 18, 2009.</ref>\nOther musicians who have toured with her as part of her band include Eric Robinson (guitar and keys),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jdmanagement.com/ericrobinson/ |title=Joe D'Ambrosio Management \u2013 Eric Robinson |publisher=Jdmanagement.com |date= |accessdate=September 30, 2011}}</ref> Holly Conlan (backing vocals), Steve Goold (drums, percussion) and Philip Krohnengold (guitar and keyboards).<ref>Philip Krohnengold. [http://krohnengold.net/ \"fil krohnengold \u2013 secret weapon\"]</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Bareilles parted amicably with her longtime bandmates to \"move in a new direction\".<ref name=\"newband\">{{citation|url=http://www.theweekender.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?avis=TL&date=20130508&category=NEWS&lopenr=305089949&Ref=AR|archive-url=https://archive.is/20131013230424/http://www.theweekender.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?avis=TL&date=20130508&category=NEWS&lopenr=305089949&Ref=AR|url-status=dead|archive-date=October 13, 2013|title=RALPHIE REPORT: Back to the start for Bareilles|accessdate=October 14, 2013|publisher=The Weekender|year=2013}}</ref> She subsequently embarked on a short solo tour, before forming a new band in anticipation of her fall co-headlining tour with [[OneRepublic]].<ref name=\"touronerepublic\">{{citation|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sara-bareilles-how-a-rough-586403|title=Sara Bareilles on How a 'Rough Year' Inspired Her Most Personal Album Yet (Q&A)|accessdate=October 14, 2013|publisher=The Hollywood Reporter|year=2013}}</ref><br>The new band consists of these personnel aside from Bareilles herself:\n* Rich Hinman (guitar),\n* Steve Goold (drums, percussion),\n* Chris Morrissey (bass),\n* Cara Fox and Christina Courtin (strings), and\n* Misty Boyce (keyboards).<ref>{{cite AV media |people=|year=2013 |title=Manhanttan, Uncharted, Eden and I Choose You (San Diego, CA) |trans-title=|medium=YouTube|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Uj1T7a5nEx4 |accessdate=January 18, 2014 |format= |time=6:23 }}</ref>\n\n===Collaborations with other artists===\nIn December 2008, a single Bareilles had performed in collaboration with Ingrid Michaelson, titled \"Winter Song\", was released from the compilation ''The Hotel Cafe Presents Winter Songs''. Bareilles and Michaelson performed it on ''The Tonight Show with Jay Leno'', and an animated video was released. In December 2011, \"Winter Song\" reached number 2 on the [[Irish Singles Chart]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://irma.ie/aucharts.asp |title=Irish Top 50 Singles |publisher=[[Irish Recorded Music Association]] |accessdate=December 14, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120511020134/http://irma.ie/aucharts.asp |archivedate=May 11, 2012 }}</ref> She also recorded a song \"Come Home\", a duet with [[OneRepublic]], which was released on iTunes on July 14, 2009.\n\nBareilles performed with many other singers on the season 3 finale of ''[[30 Rock]]'', alongside [[Mary J. Blige]], [[Rachael Yamagata]], [[Sheryl Crow]], [[Norah Jones]], and [[Elvis Costello]]. She also appeared with [[Weezer]] on ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live]]'' and as an AOL Sessions guest, performing \"[[(If You're Wondering If I Want You To) I Want You To]]\" as well for a special performance on YouTube.\n\nShe has performed for the [[First Family of the United States|First Family]] numerous times. Bareilles was first invited by First Lady [[Michelle Obama]] to play at the [[G-20 Summit]] in [[Pittsburgh]] in September 2009. Here she performed songs for the [[First Lady|First Ladies]] of 20 nations and afterward dined with Michelle Obama. The Obamas again invited her to perform at the [[Easter Egg Roll#United States|Easter Egg Roll]] in 2010. On October 20, 2010, it was announced that Bareilles would open for President [[Barack Obama|Obama]] at a Las Vegas rally for the Democratic midterm elections.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20101020/ap_on_en_mu/us_nevada_obama_visit_5|title=Singer Sara Bareilles to open for Obama in Vegas|agency=Associated Press}}</ref> In late 2010, as [[pop rock]] band [[Maroon 5]] was touring in promotion for their ''[[Hands All Over (album)|Hands All Over]]'' album, Bareilles contributed to the female vocals (originally belonging to [[Lady Antebellum]]) for the song \"Out of Goodbyes\". She appeared with the band Sugarland for a cover of [[Dexys Midnight Runners|Dexys (Midnight Runners)]]'s \"Come on Eileen\" in a YouTube exclusive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TMDqkBjvdMg |title=Sugarland with Sara Bareilles \u2013 Come on Eileen |publisher=Youtube.com}}</ref> In December, Bareilles and fellow singer Ingrid Michaelson performed \"Winter Song\" for the Obamas and many spectators at the [[National Christmas Tree (United States)|National Christmas Tree]] Lighting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenationaltree.org/ |title=The National Christmas Tree |publisher=Thenationaltree.org |date= |accessdate=September 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2010, Bareilles appeared on the second-season finale of ''[[The Sing-Off (season 2)|The Sing-Off]]'' to sing \"King of Anything\" with The Backbeats. She performed the duet \"Love Won't Let You Get Away\" with [[Seth MacFarlane]] on his debut studio album, ''[[Music Is Better Than Words]]'', and reunited to perform the song with him at [[L.A. Live#Nokia Theatre and Club Nokia|Club Nokia]] on March 26, 2011. She joined ''The Sing-Off'' as a judge in its third season alongside musicians [[Ben Folds]] and [[Shawn Stockman]] (of [[Boyz II Men]]). She and Folds sang the [[Frank Loesser]] classic \"[[Baby, It's Cold Outside]]\" on a Christmas-themed episode of the show in December 2011. Folds later produced, played on, and provided backing vocals on Bareilles' 2012 EP ''Once Upon Another Time''. Folds also provided the forward to her 2015 book, ''Sounds Like Me: My Life (So Far) In Song''.\n\nBareilles was featured on \"Summer is Over,\" the first single from [[Jon McLaughlin]]'s third studio album, ''[[Promising Promises]]'', a re-issue of his self-released album ''[[Forever If Ever]]''. McLaughlin released the selection in January 2012.\n\nMacFarlane's [[Christmas music|Christmas]] album ''[[Holiday for Swing]]'', released on September 30, 2014, would also feature Bareilles.<ref name=\"holidayforswingelusivedisc\">{{cite web|title=Seth MacFarlane Holiday For Swing LP|url=http://www.elusivedisc.com/Seth-MacFarlane-Holiday-For-Swing-LP/productinfo/UNILP70137/|publisher=elusivedisc.com|accessdate=August 29, 2014}}</ref> She joined him on another rendition of \"Baby, It's Cold Outside\". The album, which also featured collaborations with [[Norah Jones]] and [[Frank Sinatra]]'s bassist Chuck Berghoffer as well as a 65-piece orchestra, was recorded at [[Abbey Road Studios]] in London.<ref name=\"billboard8-29-2014\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6229386/seth-macfarlane-on-recording-holiday-for-swing-album|title=Seth MacFarlane on Playing It Straight for His New 'Holiday for Swing' Album|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|last=Hampp|first=Andrew|date=August 26, 2014|accessdate=August 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\nBareilles collaborated with Folds again in January 2018 at [[The Kennedy Center]] for his ''DECLASSIFIED: Ben Folds Presents'' concert series with the [[National Symphony Orchestra]]. Joined by violinist, singer, and [[Pulitzer Prize for Music|Pulitzer Prize]]-winning composer [[Caroline Shaw]], the orchestra performed classical music, modern compositions by Shaw, and five of Bareilles's songs, including \"She Used to Be Mine\" from ''Waitress''. Shaw and Dominic Mekky would arrange the orchestral parts for a performance of \"Love Song\". Shaw and Folds joined the orchestra, on vocals and percussion respectively, to back Bareilles on \"Brave\". She, Folds, and Shaw harmonized together on \"Once Upon Another Time\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Bowenbank|first=Starr|url=https://dcmetrotheaterarts.com/2018/01/14/moment-report-declassified-ben-folds-sara-bareilles-kennedy-center/ |title=In the Moment: Report on 'Declassified' with Ben Folds and Sara Bareilles at The Kennedy Center|publisher=DCMetroTheaterArts.com|date=January 14, 2018|accessdate=October 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBareilles was in a relationship with former band member and guitarist Javier Dunn until 2013.<ref name=\"Boys\">{{cite web|first=Lauren |last=Weigle |url=https://heavy.com/entertainment/2018/04/joe-tippet-sara-bareilles-boyfriend-5-fast-facts-you-need-to-know/ |title=Joe Tippet, Sara Bareilles' Boyfriend: 5 Fast Facts You Need to Know |date=April 1, 2018 |website=Heavy.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Ralphie |last=Aversa |url=http://ralphieaversa.com/2013/05/interview-sara-bareilles-gets-brave-with-new-single-home-and-tour/ |title=INTERVIEW: Sara Bareilles Gets 'Brave' With New Single, Home, and Tour |date=May 7, 2013 |website=Ralphie Aversa}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Katrina |last=Nattress |url=http://www.bestnewbands.com/interviews/javier-dunn-chats-about-signing-to-red-parade-music-and-how-sara-bareilles-changed-his-life/ |title=Javier Dunn Chats About Signing To Red Parade Music And How Sara Bareilles Changed His Life |date=June 18, 2013 |website=Best New Bands}}</ref> In August 2015, Bareilles met actor [[Joe Tippett]] during the out-of-town tryout for ''[[Waitress (musical)|Waitress]]'' at the [[American Repertory Theater]] in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]], and they later began a relationship.<ref name=\"Boys\"/><ref>{{cite web|first=Dave |last=Quinn |url=https://people.com/music/sara-bareilles-joe-tippett-dating-waitress-costar/ |title=Sugar, Butter, Flour, Love! Sara Bareilles Dating Waitress Costar Joe Tippett |date=June 14, 2017|work=People}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Taylor |last=Maple |url=https://www.bustle.com/p/whos-sara-bareilles-boyfriend-joe-tippett-is-also-in-the-theater-world-9333410 |title=Who's Sara Bareilles' Boyfriend? Joe Tippett Is Also In The Theater World  |date=June 10, 2018|work=Bustle}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Ani |last=Bundel |url=https://www.elitedaily.com/p/who-is-sara-bareilles-boyfriend-the-pair-have-adorable-story-8620370 |title=Who Is Sara Bareilles' Boyfriend? The Pair Have An Adorable Story |date=March 27, 2018|work=Elite Daily}}</ref> The couple made their first public/red carpet appearance at the 2017 [[71st Tony Awards|Tony Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Walter |last=McBride |url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Photo-Coverage-Photo-Coverage-2017-Tony-Award-Red-Carpet-Arrivals--Part-5-20170611 |title=Photo Coverage: 2017 Tony Award Red Carpet Arrivals- Part 5 |date=June 11, 2017|website=Broadway World}}</ref>\n\nBareilles considers herself \"definitely sort of a [[Feminism|feminist]],\" saying, \"I don't think that being a feminist has anything to do with hating anything. It's about celebrating women and being productive for females. I'm not one for seeing amazing, intelligent women being reduced to sex symbols.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Crystal |last=Bell |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/10/19/sara-bareilles-talks-sing-off_n_1016060.html |title=Sara Bareilles Talks 'The Sing-Off,' Feminism & Her Low Tolerance For 'Nasty' Reality TV Judges |date=October 19, 2011 |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |accessdate=May 28, 2015}}</ref> Bareilles has been a longtime ally of the LGBT community, and cites her song \"Brave\" as being inspired by her friend's struggle with [[coming out]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pridesource.com/article.html?article=73598|title=Q&A: Sara Bareilles Talks Gay 'Brothers and Sisters,' Whether Closeted Celebs Are 'Brave' & Why She Thinks Taylor Swift Stands For 'Sisterhood'|website=Pridesource|accessdate=March 2, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theseattlelesbian.com/sara-bareilles-brave-was-inspired-by-close-friends-coming-out/|title=Sara Bareilles: 'Brave' was Inspired By Close Friend's Coming Out|website=The Seattle Lesbian|accessdate=March 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Sara Bareilles discography}}\n* ''[[Careful Confessions]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Little Voice (album)|Little Voice]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Kaleidoscope Heart]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[The Blessed Unrest]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[What's Inside: Songs from Waitress]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Amidst the Chaos]]'' (2019)\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Television and film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%\" \n|-\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Notes\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 2004\n|''[[Girl Play]]''\n|The singer in the bar\n|\n|-\n|''Fairytale''\n|Princess\n|[[Video short]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 2008\n|''Walmart Soundcheck''\n|Herself\n|Episode: \"Sara Bareilles\" \n|-\n|''[[Lipstick Jungle (TV series)|Lipstick Jungle]]''\n|Herself\n|Episode:\"Chapter Nine: Help!\"\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[30 Rock]]''\n|Herself\n|Episode: \"[[Kidney Now!]]\"\n|-\n|rowspan=3| 2011\